title: Travel pill case with tight closure

description.text: This holds all the vitamins, supplements, and prescription pills I need for a full day, plus extra spots for those things it's good to have on hand (like aspirin or Tums).  The lid slides into place and should hold fairly securely, so it can go into a backpack, fanny pack, purse, etc. without worry that it'll let the pills slide out, but with a thumb-grip tab to easily tug it open.  Should be an easy print with no overhangs, hinges, etc. to worry about.
Easy print.  You might need to slightly file the outer edge of the lid to make it slide smoothly.

description.text: This a new version of my universal spool holder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:378776 This spool holder is using 4 standard 608zz roller/skate ball bearings to limit friction. This new version is larger by default and clips onto the beam to be a lot more stable.

Notes: Print two sides and optionally two rollers. The rollers adds stability to the spool. Print them if you are not using a rigid spool or if the flanges of your spool are not exactly parallel.To print the side parts it could useful to add a brim with FDM otherwise the clips may not stick well to the print bed. Insert the bearings onto the pegs. They are designed to hold them firmly. If you want to limit the friction to a minimum the best is to use dry ball bearings (remove the covers and dissolve the grease in acetone or d-limonene). In theory your spool holder is ready but if you plan on using it without the plastic rollers make sure the flanges of your spool are exactly parallel (they often are not !) otherwise you will risk a drop and to brake anything fragile beneath. Clip the support sides onto the beam and space them so that the flanges will lie onto the bearings. You can put any spool size on it, you are just limited by the size of the frame.

This is a remix of the base part from thing:414552, by @falcon20cne. Head over to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:414552 to get the spinner part. Here in New Zealand, we use different hose fittings to @falcon20cne's. I also wanted the part to print without any (additional) supports. This is the case if printed in the orientation shown in the print bed photo. I printed at 200ºC in PLA — a 190-220ºC version, obtained from http://reeltoreal.co.nz. I love this stuff! The walls a pretty thick, so I don't think the print settings you choose will matter much. This part was tested at maximum pressure available at home (quite high). I used 3 layers top and bottom and 2 perimeters, in Slic3r – oh and a 0.6mm nozzle at about 30mm/s. Any nozzle 0.6mm or smaller should work out just fine. In my case, I made the screw hole in the base 2.5mm, such that an M3x30 stainless steel cap screw goes in tight, without any lock nuts. I added a stainless washer on top, just under the screw head in the final version, though it doesn't seem to be needed with PLA setting as hard as it does. There is an access port to the screw hole in the bottom of the base, which I intended to use for injecting some loctite™. But I didn't needed it. This is the first thread I've ever printed. It is our standard, British based hose thread, namely a BSP 3/4" 14TPI. I was astonished just how well the thread came out (when printed horizontally) and just how beautifully the (yellow) hose fitting screws on. It couldn't be a better or smoother fit.

description.text: This is a set of herringbone gears similar to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10538 but done entirely in openscad based loosely on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6544 UPDATED 25/12/2011 uploaded my latest script which I've worked on a lot. It's generating some nice gears now. Also updated the STL, ratio is 45:11, nut trap should fit perfectly straight off the bed now.

Printing hints:
This is a detailed part (due to the tooth profiles) so use your smallest nozzle.
Print in PLA, it will last a lot longer due to being harder than ABS.
Set 0 extra shells (skeinforge)/ 1 perimeter (slic3r) because you can get hollow teeth with extra shells/perimeters.
Use 80-90% infill. I've already removed lots of plastic, what's left is what's needed. If your infill is too low, the most likely failure is the nut trap in the small gear will break.
You'll need really good cooling to do the base of the small gear properly. When the large gear is finished, crank your fan up to max, perhaps convince your slicer to slow it down a little too.

Combines the latest versions of my truss modules with my interlocking connectors (flush version) to create a truss that (in theory) can be printed out and multiple pieces snapped together to create lengths that can't be printed.
EDIT: Updated code for calculating the length of the truss. You specify the "max length", which is the distance you want to span, and it makes sure the length of one connector is taken into account, under the assumption that the overlapping ends are recessed into the connector on the next truss. Or if you want to think of it another way, half of each connector is taken into account, assuming you leave them the same size.
EDIT: The solid truss .scad and V3 .stl have the connectors rotated so they are printable without crazy bridging and filing down. Trusses now interlock alternating with every truss connected at 180 degrees rotated along the truss axis from it's neighbor. To connect them, I press them finger tight (about halfway inserted) then lay them flat on a table and hammer it home with my fist. :-P So far, they seem to be impossible to separate without breaking the truss, and even then I haven't actually separated them. Which was sort of the idea of a locking connector.

First off, you want the solid truss files, not the original design which was much less printable. It remains here in case anyone (maybe even myself) wants to download the code to create point-to-point cylinders or just wants to see how it's done.
You might want to attach the connectors to designs of your own that you can then link together with these truss segments.
This is parametric! The truss and connectors can be scaled to accommodate the lengths, widths, and heights you need for strength or scale reasons. Additionally, I haven't intended the example file to be printed without modifications. It may have impossible overhangs or need to be rotated.

description.text: After dealing with allot of curled / warped edges on my prints, I (and others as well) have discovered a pretty good solution.  It seems that air swirling around inside the print area causes your prints to cool unevenly and then warp during the print process.  Now to be truthful this has not completely eliminated the warping issue but it's stopped about 95% of it.  In order to use these fan ducts properly, you must turn around your fans so that they pull air through the heat sink toward the duct.  The hot air will then be blown directly out the top of the machine (in my case a MakerBot Replicator 2X).  I've enclosed the original SolidWorks file as well in case anyone wants to modify the design.  These printed very well for me with support material and a raft on the standard resolution default settings in makerware.  The duct is designed to be a "press fit".  Carefully press the duct over the 40mm fan body while watching for pinched wires.  I left the stock fan covers off as well...no reason to have them on anymore.  These work well when printed with ABS - I have not tried PLA.  Hope they work for you too!

Attaching this should help with the iMAX's life span helping it keep cool to reduce the chance of a capacitor bursting to the constant high heat. I also think it looks cool; like a turbo or a jet. I have attached the 123d file so you can edit the file however you may wish. INSTRUCTIONS:
1.To install just remove the original plate where the power connects to.
2.Hot glue/epoxy the fan in place.
3.Then just connect the wires to the two circular (metallic) holes, then solder it in place
4.Just screw in the new plate with the fan connected and attached to the plate aannd done. If you may wish one could drill holes in the opposite metal plate to increase ventilation. The fan from eBay I used:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/Brushless-DC-Blower-Cooling-Fan-40mm-x-40mm-x-20mm-4020-12V-2pin-sleeve-bearing-/251077716166?hash=item3a7565e8c6

Description:  
There are several files here: a combined door and window on a single file, a door alone, a window alone and the window components on three separate  files.  
The window can be assembled to slide open and closed.  
The scale is 1/2 inch = 1 foot. For dollhouse scale (1 inch = 1 foot) just double the scale in your slicer application. The single files are included to allow the larger scale to fit on a smaller build plate.

Print these out with 100% fill.  
The door can be reversed by mirroring it in your slicer app, and a door with both faces can be built by gluing one of each orientation together back to back.  
The window is assembled by placing the frame face down and placing the lower (sliding) sash under the upper sash with both at the top of the frame. The lower sash acts as a spacer for the upper sash placement. Glue the upper sash to the frame being careful not to use too much glue which will seep through to the lower sash. When the upper sash is held securely, move the lower sash down to the sill of the frame and glue the rails to the frame, again being careful to keep glue from the sash.  
The lower sash should now slide freely up and down in the frame.

description.text:
My last hot end.

Temperatures were taken with a thermocouple in direct contact with the inside of the nozzle.

The temperature measured at the end of the threaded M6 rod, stabilises at 46Â°C above the room temperature when the hot end is kept at 250Â°C.

I had to set the temperature at 273Â°C in order to reach 250Â°C.
But I used the distribution table for the thermistor.

The heating bloc is traced at 4, 6, 6, 4mm.
Thermistor and resistors were glued with thermally conductive silicone adhesive. Resistors AS-2 http://www.irctt.com/file.aspx?product_id=481&file_type=datasheet
Thermistor B57560G0104
Â  Â  Â  http://datasheet.octopart.com/B57560G104F-EPCOS-datasheet-16188.pdf
MACOR http://www.technicalproductsinc.com/pdf/macor.pdf
Insulation tape T-FG-SG-M051-32-X
Â  Â  Â  http://www.firesleeveandtape.com/AB-Thermal-catalog-T-FG-BM.pdf
Thermally conductive EP36AN http://www.masterbond.com/sg/masterbond_tcsg.pdf Insulation tape was glued with Hardex 650Â°F red silicone.
Remove carefully the isolation where the mozzle fits. I used a 10mm punch with the nozzle in place.
The connection between the two resistors must be crimped the others connections can be soldered. UPDATE: It's not working as expected!
a) When you extrude at full speed the heat transfert is not fast enough.
b) PLA get clogged inside of the stainless steel thread if the temperature is set higher than 200Â°C.
So, I redesigned it.
1) I kept the resistor bloc that works great.
2) The nozzle has now a M6 tail of 20mm. His head size is 10mm and drilled at 0.4mm.
3) The thermal barrier is machined in MACOR and has 35mm long.
4) To avoid clogging a teflon tube of 3.4/3.8 is inserted inside the thermal barrier and the threaded part of the nozzle. I will post a new drawing as soon as possible.

title: Wheelbarrow Headlight Using Eveready 6V Flashlight Guts

description.text: In the deep dark cold of winter, stumbling out to the woodshed in the pitch black isn't so fun. So I made a headlight for my wheelbarrow using the guts of an Eveready 6V flashlight (see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1071036 ). There are many unprinted versions of the housing for the light -- the one seen here is the one named "bell housing with beefed up attachment post". The parts are painted with inexpensive appliance epoxy paint for weather proofing reasons. I wouldn't have really chosen beige except it was that or white, and I figured white would be silly on a wheelbarrow. For the other versions of the lens housing, lighter posts are fine for non-vibrating uses. There are also some versions where the post and the housing are separate pieces which can be epoxied together later -- these will save support material.

This is a miniature monster truck that has been 100% 3D printed. It has four sets of working wheels and suspension, the suspension travel is about 20mm. The monster truck was printed in 30 separate parts and took over 100 hours of printing time! All the parts were made from ABS except for the orange wheel covers which were made from NinjaFlex, these covers took 10 hours each and aren’t strictly necessary but they do add a rubbery feel to the wheels and increase traction.
More of my models are available at www.trinpy.com
All the parts have been made to clip together so that no glue or other joining method is necessary. However this model was sealed with and ABS and acetone slurry to get the smooth shiny finish and cover the gaps on the monster truck body. Then the whole truck was placed in an acetone bath to get a smooth finish all over. The body was printed in three separate parts as the whole truck is much to large to print on a standard desktop printer. The wheels slip onto the suspension linkage as do the springs, then the wheels are attached with the round clips included in the zip file. Then the suspension assembly slides up into the body of the truck and once you hear the ‘click’ means it is assembled and ready to rock!
